      <h2>Introduction to Foundation</h2>
      <p>The “Sanxia Li Mei-Shu Memorial Hall” established since 1990 is a personal art gallery representing Taiwan, which has been officially designated into a “local cultural museum” under the Department of Cultural Affairs, adding a new leisure, education and tourism scenic spots for New Taipei City.</p>
      <p>Li Mei-Shu has devoted his lifetime of efforts in the reconstruction project of Sanxia Zushi Temple with enthusiasm in charity. He served as county councilman and farmers’ association director to provide services to fellowmen, followed by instructing at the National Art College (now the National Taiwan University of Arts). Chinese Culture University and National Normal University. In his lifelong career, Li has been an artist, educator, politician, and temple architect whose 81 years of remarkable art career opened up a brilliant and legendary chapter in the art history of Taiwan. In commemoration of the predecessor’s spirit and many works and relics, the family of Li raised their own funds since 1990 to establish the Li Mei-Shu Memorial Gallery in Sanxia Township, followed by establishing the Li Mei-Shu Cultural and Educational Foundation even today.</p>
      <p>Gallery Director Mr. Li Jing-Guang stated that the difficulty encountered by Li Mei-Shu Memorial Gallery included “space,” “funds” and “legacy.” Since Li Mei-Shu seldom sold paintings or exhibited his painting before passing away but he intended to preserve his works with him, the three brothers and five sisters intended to operate sustainable management of Li Mei-Shu Memorial Gallery in spite of the difficulties.</p>
      <p>Currently the establishment of Li Mei Shu Relics Memorial Museum is being prepared at Minsheng Street, Sanxia, which exhibits the antique relics collected by the family to contribute efforts in the passing of Taiwan’s culture.</p>
      <p>Li Mei-Shu Cultural and Educational Foundation is committed to the safeguard and preservation of works from Mr. Li Mei-Shu. “Li Mei-Shu’s hand-drawn Sanxia Zushi Temple Design Draft” reproduces the most primitive artistic concept of Zushi Temple with proof on the ingenuity of mutual fusion between the creation and living space by artists.</p>
      <p>Hand-drawn drafts are safe-guarded by Li Mei-Shu Cultural and Educational Foundation and the National Library, where the yellowed paper and faint traces of the drawing are reproduced to the lifelong commitment of artist Li Mei-Shu in care for local and art movement, demonstrating the most zeal warmth of life.</p>
      <p>We look forward to art fans of all industries to make contribution to Li Mei-Shu Cultural and Educational Foundation.</p>
